IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
On Sunday June, 25, 2023 at approximately 1140 hours, I, TFC. Lowe #6739, was in uniform of the day. At that time, I responded to a serious motor vehicle collision involving a motorcycle in the area of W/B Rt. 50 and Bay Dale Dr., Arnold, MD 21012. I arrived on scene on the Eastbound side of Rt. 50. EMS units had lane 1 of Eastbound Rt. 50 shut down and lanes 1 and 2 of W/B Rt. 50 shut down. When I walked to the scene, I observed a red Harley-Davidson motorcycle near the guardrail with damage. EMS unit were doing CPR on a male victim laying on his back in the grass against the guardrail. At 1147 hours, Tim Kinsey #1365 of Anne Arundel County EMS declared the subject deceased. At 1143 hours, I requested a re-constructionist to respond to the scene. At 1228 hours, the medical examiner advised she was en route to the scene from Harford County. The red Harley displayed a Virginia registration of "V405." Also, on scene was a female witness. The female was identified by her Virginia license as, Lucinda Freeman, W/F, DOB: 10/29/1977. Freeman advised that she was friends with the victim and identified him as, Dale Alan Angell, W/M, DOB: 06/09/1961. Freeman stated that she was driving her motorcycle behind Angell and Angell's Girlfriend, Mary, was traveling in front of him, on her bike. Freeman stated that they were in lane 3 heading W/B Rt. 50 near Bay Dale Dr. when traffic was beginning to merge from Bay Dale Dr. onto W/B Rt. 50, and she observed Angell shift his weight from lane 3 to the next lane. Freeman stated that when he did this, she observed his body go limp over the gas tank of the motorcycle and the bike traveled off the roadway, across lanes 1 and 2. Freeman said that the bike struck the guardrail, ejected Angell, and flew another 20 feet in front of him. Freeman filled out a witness statement while on scene. Angell's girlfriend stopped her motorcycle on Rt. 2 but advised that she did not want to come back to the scene and that she was afraid to drive her bike. At 1306 hours, TFC.Baldi #6907, arrived on scene to complete his investigation. At 1350 hours, the Medical Examiner arrived on scene. Once the Medical Examiner completed her assessment, Rodney Orlando Ward, B/M, DOB: 05/14/1970, arrived on scene to transport the body to the Chief Medical Examiner's Office. After the body was bagged and strapped to the gurney to be placed into the transport van, Rodney Ward, unexpectedly passed out and fell to the ground. EMS on scene provided treatment and determined he needed to be transported to the hospital. Medic 12 transported Ward to AAMC and Ward's wife took possession of the transport van to take the deceased to the Medical Examiner's Office. Marc Bowen Towing removed the motorcycle from the scene and transported it to the tow lot. At 1523 hours, all lanes on Rt. 50 were reopened. 

All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, MD.

Detailed Crash Investigation Report


Section I. - Introduction: 
On June 25, 2023 at approximately 1137 hours, the Maryland State Police Annapolis Barrack “J” received reports of a single-vehicle collision in the area of westbound US-50 at Bay Dale Dr in Annapolis, Anne Arundel County, Maryland. The first to arrive on-scene was Trooper First Class K. Jeans #6483 and E. Lowe #6739. Upon arrival to the scene and the severity of the collision, a request for an advance collision investigator was made to respond to the scene. At approximately 1143 hours, I Trooper First Class A. J. Baldi #6907 was notified and responded.
Section II. - Scene Description: (The following descriptions are based on the area where the collision occurred.)

Primary Roadway: 
Westbound Bluestar Memorial Highway (US-50) is described as a multi-lane road that is traveled east to west. The eastbound and westbound sides are separated by a positive median barrier which consists of a concrete a guardrail assembly. The left shoulder is clearly and visibly marked with a solid yellow lane line. Lanes 1 through 3 are divided by broken white lane lines. The right shoulder is clearly and visibly marked with a solid white fog line. The right shoulder consists of a grassy shoulder and a concrete.
 

Secondary Roadway (if applicable): 
Not applicable.

Environmental Conditions:
Per weather underground, the temperature at the time of the collision was 89 degrees Fahrenheit. The lighting conditions consisted of sunlight. The sky was clear with no precipitation forecasted.

 
Section III. - Scene Evidence:
When I arrived I immediately began to photograph and mark the scene evidence. No obvious pre-impact braking evidence was discovered while processing the scene. Additionally, no post-impact gouge marks could be seen other than debris scattered from the vehicles. Note- the images below provide a basic depiction of the travel of Angell's motorcycle and the evidence located on the roadway.


This image represents the direction of travel of Angell's motorcycle.

In this image, a visible blood sneer can be seen leading from lane 2 to lane 3.

This image shows a paint transfer that was located on the asphalt. A set of trauma sheers was placed next to it for size comparison.
Section IV. - Vehicle(s) Involved:

Vehicle #1:
Red 2010 Harley-Davidson FLHRC VA registration “Z405” 1HD1FR418AB623851


After reviewing the Harley-Davidson, Minor damage was observed on the motorcycle. I observed scratches to the paint on the front fender. The right side of the motorcycle also sustained damage from contacting the asphalt when the collision events occurred.
Section V. - Person(s) Involved:

Person #1: 
Rider: Dale A Angell (W/M DOB: 06/09/1962) Deceased
Angell was the sole rider on the motorcycle. After the collision events occurred he was subsequently pronounced deceased at the scene by Paramedic Tim Kensley #1365 with the Anne Arundel County Fire Department at 1147 hours. Angell was transported from the scene to the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner in Baltimore City, Maryland for an autopsy investigation to be conducted.


Person #2:

Lucinda Anne Freeman (W/F DOB: 10/29/1977) Witness
Freeman was a witness who was interviewed by both TFC Lowe and me. She was asked to complete a written statement. The statement was collected and uploaded to this report.

During an interview with Freeman, She stated Angell, Mary, and she were riding on westbound US-50 in the area of Bay Dale Drive, traveling at approximately 50/55 Miles Per Hour. She said she observed Angell start to merge into lane 1 and was leaning over the left of his motorcycle. She said the motorcycle continued and traveled off-road onto the left shoulder striking the guardrail. After the collision events, Freeman called 911 and requested assistance for Angell and attempted to keep traffic moving while she waited for Paramedics to arrive.

Person #3:
Jason T Fehr (W/M DOB 04/27/1977) Witness

Fehr was interviewed on-scene prior to my arrival by TFC’s Lowe and Jeans. A statement completed by Fehr was uploaded to this report.

The interview with Fehr and his statement revealed he was traveling in the area after the collision events occurred. He noticed the scene and stopped to assist. he advised he assisted with providing chest compressions until EMS arrived on scene.
Section VI. - Follow-up Investigation:

Date:
August 17th, 2023 Autopsy received from OCME.

At the conclusion of the autopsy investigation completed on 07/31/23 by Theodor M Knight Jr M.D, Angell's death was caused as a result of multiple injuries related to the collision events. His death was ruled as an ''accident''. At the conclusion of Dr. Knight's opinion, he states Angell's postmortem toxicology revealed he did have a small amount of alcohol in his blood. The value was noted as (0.02% W/V).


 
Section VII. - Analysis of Electronic Control Modules:

Due to the nature of the collision, none of the involved vehicles were imaged.

 
Section VIII. - Speed Analysis:

Due to the lack of roadway and pre-impact breaking evidence, a speed analysis was unable to be conducted.
Section IX. - Crash Dynamics:

The on-scene investigation revealed Angell was traveling westbound on US-50 at Bay Dale Rd when, for an unknown reason lost control of his 2010 Harley-Davidson bearing VA registration “Z405”. The motorcycle rolled to the right onto the frame and continued from lane 2 to the left shoulder for approximately 79.9 feet. A visible paint transfer and blood smear was located on the pavement. The motorcycle then struck the guardrail causing Angell to be ejected onto the shoulder under the guardrail assembly. The motorcycle continued an additional 20.2 feet when it came to an uncontrolled final rest.  
 
Section X. - Attachments that were included in for this report:

The following items were attached to this report:

-Written statements collected at the scene were uploaded to this report.
-ACRS report authored by TFC Lowe was uploaded to this report.
-Detailed Crash Diagram was uploaded to this report.
-OCME Autopsy report.


 
Conclusion:
The following conclusions are based upon the totality of the investigation, including the statements of persons involved, the physical evidence accumulated. My rendering of these conclusions are based upon my training in the field of advanced collision investigation and are to a reasonable degree of scientific certainty.

On June 25th, 2023, at 1137 hours. A red Harley Davidson operated by Dale A Angell (W/M DOB: 06/09/1962) was traveling westbound on US-50 at Bay Dale Rd in lane 2. Witnesses stated they observed Angell lean over the fuel tank of the motorcycle and lose control and travel off-road and struck the guardrail. As a result, Angell suffered injuries as a result of the collision that were not compatible with sustaining life and subsequently succumbed to his injuries. The collision events are as result of Angell failing to control his motorcycle and striking the guardrail assembly.



This case is closed due to the death of at-fault party.
